:"Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1525":"1525","1558":"1558","7 July 1558":"7. juli 1558","1501":"1501","1497":"1497","1573":"1573","1560":"1560","1549":"1549","Tretherffe, Ladock, Cornwall, England":"Ladock, Cornwall, England","England":"England","Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England","Ashford, Devon, England":"Ashford, Devon, England"},"nl":{"1501–1560":"1501–1560","1497–1558":"1497–1558","1525–1573":"1525–1573","–Male":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1525":"1525","1558":"1558","7 July 1558":"7 juli 1558","1501":"1501","1497":"1497","1573":"1573","1560":"1560","1549":"1549","Tretherffe, Ladock, Cornwall, England":"Ladock, Cornwall, England","England":"England","Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England","Ashford, Devon, England":"Ashford, Devon, England"},"en":{"1501–1560":"1501–1560","1497–1558":"1497–1558","1525–1573":"1525–1573","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1525":"1525","1558":"1558","7 July 1558":"7 July 1558","1501":"1501","1497":"1497","1573":"1573","1560":"1560","1549":"1549","Tretherffe, Ladock, Cornwall, England":"Ladock, Cornwall, England","England":"England","Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England","Ashford, Devon, England":"Ashford, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tanner","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southern) and Dutch: occupational name for a tanner of skins, Middle English <i>tanner</i>, Middle Dutch <i>taenre</i>. The Middle English form derives from Old English <i>tannere</i>, from Late Latin <i>tannarius</i>, reinforced by Old French <i>taneor</i>, from Late Latin <i>tannator</i>; both Late Latin forms derive from a verb <i>tannare</i>, possibly from a Celtic word for the oak, whose bark was used in the process.","German: topographic name from Middle High German <i>tan</i> ‘woods, pine forest’ for someone who lived near such terrain.","German: habitational name for someone from any of several places called Tanne (in the Harz Mountains, Bavaria, East Prussia, Switzerland) or Tann (Hesse, Bavaria), Thann (Bavaria, Austria, Alsace), Tannen (southern Germany, Switzerland), Thannen (Bavaria)."],"variants":[{"name":"Tenner","meanings":["German and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Tanner   2.","English: status name from Old French <i>teneor</i>, <i>teneur</i>, <i>tenor</i> ‘tenant’, for someone who held property from a lord by feudal service, hence an equivalent of   Tennant  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Tann","meanings":["German: topographic name for someone who lived in a forest, Middle High German <i>tan</i>. This was originally a distinct word from <i>tanne</i> ‘pine tree’, and denoted a forest of any kind. Inevitably, however, the two became confused, with the result that <i>Tann</i> now denotes only coniferous forests; in this form it is a rather rare and literary word.","English (mainly Norfolk): metonymic occupational name from Middle English <i>tan(ne)</i> ‘oak bark’ (Old French <i>tan</i>), i.e. crushed oak bark used in tanning. See also   Tanner  .","English (mainly Norfolk): from the Middle English personal name <i>Tan</i>, a pet form of   Andrew  . Compare   Tandy  ."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":48,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":57,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"George William Tanner was born in 1501, in England as the son of John Tanner and Mrs. John Tanner. He had at least 1 daughter with Margaret Tregarthen. He died in 1560, in Ladock, Cornwall, England, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1501–1560":"1501–1560","1497–1558":"1497–1558","1525–1573":"1525–1573","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1525":"1525","1558":"1558","7 July 1558":"7. juuli 1558","1501":"1501","1497":"1497","1573":"1573","1560":"1560","1549":"1549","Tretherffe, Ladock, Cornwall, England":"Ladock, Cornwall, England","England":"England","Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England","Ashford, Devon, England":"Ashford, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1501–1560":"1501–1560","1497–1558":"1497–1558","1525–1573":"1525–1573","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1525":"1525","1558":"1558","7 July 1558":"7. heinäkuuta 1558","1501":"1501","1497":"1497","1573":"1573","1560":"1560","1549":"1549","Tretherffe, Ladock, Cornwall, England":"Ladock, Cornwall, England","England":"England","Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England","Ashford, Devon, England":"Ashford, Devon, England"},"fr":{"1501–1560":"1501–1560","1497–1558":"1497–1558","1525–1573":"1525–1573","–Male":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1525":"1525","1558":"1558","7 July 1558":"7 juillet 1558","1501":"1501","1497":"1497","1573":"1573","1560":"1560","1549":"1549","Tretherffe, Ladock, Cornwall, England":"Ladock, Cornouailles, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre","Ashford, Devon, England":"Ashford, Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"George William Tanner est né en 1501, à Angleterre,